Context
"The Lever" is a newsletter/media brand by Kyle and Reese covering AI, automation, and marketing for local businesses (restaurants, salons, clinics, trades). A single HTML landing page exists. The goal: transform it into a full editorial website — "an entire world" — that feels alive, distinctive, and fun. Built to last 20 years.
Core durability principle: Pure HTML5 + CSS3 + vanilla JS. No build tools, no npm, no frameworks. Self-hosted fonts. Flat files. Nothing to break, nothing to upgrade.

Creative Direction — What Makes This Not Generic
Design: "Children's Book for Business Owners"
The existing page is beautiful but editorial-safe. We're pushing it toward whimsical warmth — the feeling of a well-loved children's book crossed with a smart newsletter. Think Oliver Jeffers meets Monocle magazine.
Signature design elements:

Inline SVG illustrations — hand-drawn-style decorative elements (not clip art, not icons). A wobbly lever/fulcrum motif. Squiggly underlines. Small doodle-style marginalia that react to the content. These are pure SVG in the HTML — resolution-independent forever.
Oversized pull quotes — Fraunces at massive optical size, rotated slightly, breaking out of the content column. Not centered and polite — bold and angled.
Playful hover states — article cards that tilt slightly on hover (CSS transform: rotate(-1deg)), buttons that bounce (scale(1.05)), navigation items that do a subtle wiggle.
Color personality per column — each column doesn't just get a dot color, it gets a full mood. Signal gets terra cotta warmth. Field Notes gets olive earthiness. The Lab gets plum mystery. These tint the entire page when you're in that column's world.
"Scribbled" borders — CSS border-image with an SVG wavy/hand-drawn line instead of straight rules. The whole site feels like notes in a beloved notebook.
Surprise details — the 404 page has a lever that's broken. The footer has a tiny animated lever that tips when you scroll to it. The issue number on the homepage has a hand-drawn circle around it.
Big, bold numbers — issue numbers, statistics in articles, and data points are rendered HUGE in Fraunces with the optical size cranked to 144. Like a children's book teaching you to count.
Paper texture + subtle grain — keep the existing paper texture but add warm shadows that make elements feel like they're sitting ON the paper, not printed into it.

Voice: Sabri Suby Meets Shaan Puri in a Burger Joint
The copy should feel like the smartest person at the bar telling you something wild they discovered this week. Not academic. Not corporate. Not "content marketing."
Voice principles (inspired by Sabri Suby, Shaan Puri, Chris Von Wilpert, Neville Medhora):

Lead with the story, not the lesson (Shaan Puri) — "A restaurant owner didn't notice his phone was being answered by AI. For four days." Not "How AI Phone Answering Can Help Your Restaurant."
Bold claims backed by numbers (Sabri Suby / Chris Von Wilpert) — "312 calls. 41 reservations." Not "significant improvement in bookings."
Conversational and irreverent (Neville Medhora) — "Most were bad. A few were really bad. But the ones that worked changed how we think about creative." Not "Results were mixed but promising."
Create a curiosity gap (Shaan Puri) — "Not backlinks. Not content. Something most SEOs aren't tracking yet." The reader HAS to click.
Every piece triggers an emotion (Shaan Puri's 7 emotions) — "OHHH now I get it", "WOW that's amazing", "FINALLY someone said it."
Talk about what they LOSE by not reading (Sabri Suby) — "Your competitors are about to get very good at this."
Practical specifics over vague advice (Chris Von Wilpert) — "$4 at one place. $94 at another. Same neighbourhood. Same food."

Differentiation from every.to
every.to is sleek, minimalist, tech-forward — designed for developers and AI researchers. The Lever is:

Warmer — paper textures, hand-drawn elements, earth tones vs. every.to's clean white/black
More playful — whimsical illustrations, tilting cards, surprise animations vs. every.to's restrained Swiss design
More approachable — written for a restaurant owner or plumber, not a software engineer
More opinionated — bold claims, story-driven headlines, data that shocks vs. every.to's measured analysis


